386→                        <div id="content">For any integer $n=\prod p^{k_p}$ let $Q_2(n)$ be the powerful part of $n$, so that\[Q_2(n) = \prod_{\substack{p\\ k_p\geq 2}}p^{k_p}.\]Is it true that, for every $\epsilon&#62;0$ and $\ell\geq 1$, if $n$ is sufficiently large then\[Q_2(n(n+1)\cdots(n+\ell))&#60;n^{2+\epsilon}?\]If $\ell\geq 2$ then is\[\limsup_{n\to \infty}\frac{Q_2(n(n+1)\cdots(n+\ell))}{n^2}\]infinite? <br><br>If $\ell\geq 2$ then is\[\lim_{n\to \infty}\frac{Q_2(n(n+1)\cdots(n+\ell))}{n^{\ell+1}}=0?\]</div>
